  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "fullName": "Docker Scout",
          "informationUri": "https://docker.com/products/docker-scout",
          "name": "docker scout",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "CVE-2005-2541",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2005-2541"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2005-2541?s=debian&n=tar&ns=debian&t=deb&osn=debian&osv=13&vr=%3C%3D1.35%2Bdfsg-3.1",
              "help": {
                "text": "Tar 1.15.1 does not properly warn the user when extracting setuid or setgid files, which may allow local users or remote attackers to gain privileges.\n\n---\nThis is intended behaviour, after all tar is an archiving tool and you\nneed to give -p as a command line flag\n- tar <unfixed> (bug https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=328228; unimportant)\n",
                "markdown": "> Tar 1.15.1 does not properly warn the user when extracting setuid or setgid files, which may allow local users or remote attackers to gain privileges.\n\n---\nThis is intended behaviour, after all tar is an archiving tool and you\nneed to give -p as a command line flag\n- tar <unfixed> (bug https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=328228; unimportant)\n\n|                                                                                                  |\n|Package         pkg:deb/debian/tar@1.35%2Bdfsg-3.1?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13  |\n|Affected range  <=1.35+dfsg-3.1                                                                   |\n|Fixed version   not fixed                                                                         |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "affected_version": "<=1.35+dfsg-3.1",
                "cvssV3_severity": "LOW",
                "fixed_version": "not fixed",
                "purls": [
                  "pkg:deb/debian/tar@1.35%2Bdfsg-3.1?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13"
                ],
                "security-severity": "3.1",
                "tags": [
                  "LOW"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2007-5686",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2007-5686"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2007-5686?s=debian&n=shadow&ns=debian&t=deb&osn=debian&osv=13&vr=%3C%3D1%3A4.17.4-2",
              "help": {
                "text": "initscripts in rPath Linux 1 sets insecure permissions for the /var/log/btmp file, which allows local users to obtain sensitive information regarding authentication attempts.  NOTE: because sshd detects the insecure permissions and does not log certain events, this also prevents sshd from logging failed authentication attempts by remote attackers.\n\n---\n- shadow <unfixed> (unimportant)\nSee #290803, on Debian LOG_UNKFAIL_ENAB in login.defs is set to no so\nunknown usernames are not recorded on login failures\n",
                "markdown": "> initscripts in rPath Linux 1 sets insecure permissions for the /var/log/btmp file, which allows local users to obtain sensitive information regarding authentication attempts.  NOTE: because sshd detects the insecure permissions and does not log certain events, this also prevents sshd from logging failed authentication attempts by remote attackers.\n\n---\n- shadow <unfixed> (unimportant)\nSee #290803, on Debian LOG_UNKFAIL_ENAB in login.defs is set to no so\nunknown usernames are not recorded on login failures\n\n|                                                                                                  |\n|Package         pkg:deb/debian/shadow@1%3A4.17.4-2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13  |\n|Affected range  <=1:4.17.4-2                                                                      |\n|Fixed version   not fixed                                                                         |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "affected_version": "<=1:4.17.4-2",
                "cvssV3_severity": "LOW",
                "fixed_version": "not fixed",
                "purls": [
                  "pkg:deb/debian/shadow@1%3A4.17.4-2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13"
                ],
                "security-severity": "3.1",
                "tags": [
                  "LOW"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2010-0928",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2010-0928"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2010-0928?s=debian&n=openssl&ns=debian&t=deb&osn=debian&osv=13&vr=%3E%3D3.2.1-3",
              "help": {
                "text": "OpenSSL 0.9.8i on the Gaisler Research LEON3 SoC on the Xilinx Virtex-II Pro FPGA uses a Fixed Width Exponentiation (FWE) algorithm for certain signature calculations, and does not verify the signature before providing it to a caller, which makes it easier for physically proximate attackers to determine the private key via a modified supply voltage for the microprocessor, related to a \"fault-based attack.\"\n\n---\nhttp://www.eecs.umich.edu/~valeria/research/publications/DATE10RSA.pdf\nhttps://github.com/openssl/openssl/discussions/24540\nFault injection based attacks are not within OpenSSLs threat model according\nto the security policy: https://www.openssl.org/policies/general/security-policy.html\n",
                "markdown": "> OpenSSL 0.9.8i on the Gaisler Research LEON3 SoC on the Xilinx Virtex-II Pro FPGA uses a Fixed Width Exponentiation (FWE) algorithm for certain signature calculations, and does not verify the signature before providing it to a caller, which makes it easier for physically proximate attackers to determine the private key via a modified supply voltage for the microprocessor, related to a \"fault-based attack.\"\n\n---\nhttp://www.eecs.umich.edu/~valeria/research/publications/DATE10RSA.pdf\nhttps://github.com/openssl/openssl/discussions/24540\nFault injection based attacks are not within OpenSSLs threat model according\nto the security policy: https://www.openssl.org/policies/general/security-policy.html\n\n|                                                                                                      |\n|Package         pkg:deb/debian/openssl@3.5.5-1~deb13u2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13  |\n|Affected range  >=3.2.1-3                                                                             |\n|Fixed version   not fixed                                                                             |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "affected_version": ">=3.2.1-3",
                "cvssV3_severity": "LOW",
                "fixed_version": "not fixed",
                "purls": [
                  "pkg:deb/debian/openssl@3.5.5-1~deb13u2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13"
                ],
                "security-severity": "3.1",
                "tags": [
                  "LOW"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2010-4651",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2010-4651"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2010-4651?s=debian&n=patch&ns=debian&t=deb&osn=debian&osv=13&vr=%3C%3D2.8-2",
              "help": {
                "text": "Directory traversal vulnerability in util.c in GNU patch 2.6.1 and earlier allows user-assisted remote attackers to create or overwrite arbitrary files via a filename that is specified with a .. (dot dot) or full pathname, a related issue to CVE-2010-1679.\n\n---\n- patch <unfixed> (unimportant)\nApplying a patch blindly opens more severe security issues than only directory traversal...\nopenwall ships a fix\nSee https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=667529 for details\n",
                "markdown": "> Directory traversal vulnerability in util.c in GNU patch 2.6.1 and earlier allows user-assisted remote attackers to create or overwrite arbitrary files via a filename that is specified with a .. (dot dot) or full pathname, a related issue to CVE-2010-1679.\n\n---\n- patch <unfixed> (unimportant)\nApplying a patch blindly opens more severe security issues than only directory traversal...\nopenwall ships a fix\nSee https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=667529 for details\n\n|                                                                                          |\n|Package         pkg:deb/debian/patch@2.8-2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13  |\n|Affected range  <=2.8-2                                                                   |\n|Fixed version   not fixed                                                                 |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "affected_version": "<=2.8-2",
                "cvssV3_severity": "LOW",
                "fixed_version": "not fixed",
                "purls": [
                  "pkg:deb/debian/patch@2.8-2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13"
                ],
                "security-severity": "3.1",
                "tags": [
                  "LOW"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2010-4756",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2010-4756"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2010-4756?s=debian&n=glibc&ns=debian&t=deb&osn=debian&osv=13&vr=%3C%3D2.41-12%2Bdeb13u2",
              "help": {
                "text": "The glob implementation in the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) allows remote authenticated users to cause a denial of service (CPU and memory consumption) via crafted glob expressions that do not match any pathnames, as demonstrated by glob expressions in STAT commands to an FTP daemon, a different vulnerability than CVE-2010-2632.\n\n---\n- glibc <removed> (unimportant)\n- eglibc <unfixed> (unimportant)\nThat's standard POSIX behaviour implemented by (e)glibc. Applications using\nglob need to impose limits for themselves\n",
                "markdown": "> The glob implementation in the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) allows remote authenticated users to cause a denial of service (CPU and memory consumption) via crafted glob expressions that do not match any pathnames, as demonstrated by glob expressions in STAT commands to an FTP daemon, a different vulnerability than CVE-2010-2632.\n\n---\n- glibc <removed> (unimportant)\n- eglibc <unfixed> (unimportant)\nThat's standard POSIX behaviour implemented by (e)glibc. Applications using\nglob need to impose limits for themselves\n\n|                                                                                                      |\n|Package         pkg:deb/debian/glibc@2.41-12%2Bdeb13u2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13  |\n|Affected range  <=2.41-12+deb13u2                                                                     |\n|Fixed version   not fixed                                                                             |\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "affected_version": "<=2.41-12+deb13u2",
                "cvssV3_severity": "LOW",
                "fixed_version": "not fixed",
                "purls": [
                  "pkg:deb/debian/glibc@2.41-12%2Bdeb13u2?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13"
                ],
                "security-severity": "3.1",
                "tags": [
                  "LOW"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2011-3374",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "CVE-2011-3374"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://scout.docker.com/v/CVE-2011-3374?s=debian&n=apt&ns=debian&t=deb&osn=debian&osv=13&vr=%3C%3D3.0.3",
              "help": {
                "text": "It was found that apt-key in apt, all versions, do not correctly validate gpg keys with the master keyring, leading to a potential man-in-the-middle attack.\n\n---\n- apt <unfixed> (unimportant; bug https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=642480)\nNot exploitable in Debian, since no keyring URI is defined\n",
                "markdown": "> It was found that apt-key in apt, all versions, do not correctly validate gpg keys with the master keyring, leading to a potential man-in-the-middle attack.\n\n---\n- apt <unfixed> (unimportant; bug https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=642480)\nNot exploitable in Debian, since no keyring URI is defined\n\n|                                                                                        |\n|Package         pkg:deb/debian/apt@3.0.3?os_distro=trixie&os_name=debian&os_version=13  |\n|Affected range  <=3.0.3                                                                 |\n|Fixed version   not fixed                                                               |\n"
